            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If an integer has a remainder of 11 when it is divided by 12,
              is it possible to determine the remainder of the square of that integer when it is divided by 12?
              If so, determine the remainder and prove that your answer is correct.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>n</m> be a natural number greater than 2.
              If an integer has a remainder of <m>n - 1</m> when it is divided by <m>n</m>,
              is it possible to determine the remainder of the square of that integer when it is divided by <m>n</m>?
              If so, determine the remainder and prove that your answer is correct.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be a natural number greater than 4 and let <m>a</m> be an integer that has a remainder of <m>n - 2</m> when it is divided by <m>n</m>.
          Make whatever conclusions you can about the remainder of <m>a^2</m> when it is divided by <m>n</m>.
          Justify all conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Is the following proposition true or false?
          Justify your conclusion with a proof or a counterexample.
          <ul>
            \item For each natural number <m>n</m>, if 3 does not divide <m>\left( n^2 + 2 \right)</m>, then <m>n</m> is not a prime number or <m>n=3</m>.
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec34-new9">
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Is the following proposition true or false?
              Justify your conclusion with a counterexample or a proof.
              <ul>
                \item For each integer <m>n</m>, if <m>n</m> is odd, then <m>n^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 8</m>.
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Compare this proposition to the proposition in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_sec34-nsquared"/> from <xref ref="S_cases"></xref>.
              Are these two propositions equivalent?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Is the following proposition true or false?
              Justify your conclusion with a counterexample or a proof.
              <ul>
                \item For each integer <m>n</m>, if <m>n</m> is odd and <m>n</m> is not a multiple of 3, then <m>n^2 \equiv 1 \pmod {24}</m>.
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove the following proposition:
          <ul>
            \item For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, if 3 divides <m>\left( a^2 + b^2 \right)</m>, then 3 divides <m>a</m> and 3 divides <m>b</m>.
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_case-ind">
        <p>
          Is the following proposition true or false?
          Justify your conclusion with a counterexample or a proof.
          <ul>
            \item For each integer <m>a</m>, 3 divides <m>a^3 + 23a</m>.
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_falsecongruence">
        <p>
          Are the following statements true or false?
          Either prove the statement is true or provide a counterexample to show it is false.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a \cdot b \equiv 0 \pmod{6}</m>,
                then <m>a \equiv 0 \pmod{6}</m> or <m>b \equiv 0 \pmod{6}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a \cdot b \equiv 0 \pmod{8}</m>,
                then <m>a \equiv 0 \pmod{8}</m> or <m>b \equiv 0 \pmod{8}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a \cdot b \equiv 1 \pmod{6}</m>,
                then <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod{6}</m> or <m>b \equiv 1 \pmod{6}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>ab \equiv 7 \pmod{12}</m>,
                then either <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod{12}</m> or <m>a \equiv 7 \pmod{12}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine several pairs of integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>a \equiv b \pmod 5</m>.
              For each such pair, calculate <m>4a + b</m>,
              <m>3a + 2b</m>, and <m>7a + 3b</m>.
              Are each of the resulting integers congruent to 0 modulo 5?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove or disprove the following proposition:
              <ul>
                \item Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be integers such that <m>(m + n) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m> and let <m>a, b \in \Z</m>. If <m>a \equiv b \pmod 5</m>, then <m>(ma +nb) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>.
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Evaluation of proofs</em>  See the instructions for Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_proofeval"/> on <xref ref="exer_proofeval">page</xref>
          from <xref ref="S_directproof"></xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <em>Proposition</em>.
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>(a + 2b) \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>,
                then <m>(2a + b) \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    We assume <m>a, b \in \Z</m> and <m>(a + 2b) \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>.
                    This means that 3 divides <m>a + 2b</m> and, hence,
                    there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>a + 2b = 3m</m>.
                    Hence, <m>a = 3m - 2b</m>.
                    For <m>(2a + b) \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>,
                    there exists an integer <m>x</m> such that <m>2a + b = 3x</m>.
                    Hence,
                    <md>
                      <mrow>2(3m - 2b) + b \amp = 3x</mrow>
                      <mrow>6m - 3b \amp = 3x</mrow>
                      <mrow>3(2m - b) \amp = 3x</mrow>
                      <mrow>2m - b \amp = x</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Since <m>(2m - b)</m> is an integer,
                    this proves that 3 divides <m>(2a + b)</m> and hence,
                    <m>(2a + b) \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>.
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <em>Proposition</em>.
                For each integer <m>m</m>, 5 divides <m>\left(m^5 - m \right)</m>.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>m \in \Z</m>.
                    We will prove that 5 divides
                    <m>\left(m^5 - m \right)</m> by proving that <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>.
                    We will use cases.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    For the first case, if <m>m \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>,
                    then <m>m^5 \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m> and,
                    hence, <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    For the second case, if <m>m \equiv 1 \pmod 5</m>,
                    then <m>m^5 \equiv 1 \pmod 5</m> and, hence,
                    <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv (1 - 1) \pmod 5</m>,
                    which means that <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    For the third case, if <m>m \equiv 2 \pmod 5</m>,
                    then <m>m^5 \equiv 32 \pmod 5</m> and, hence,
                    <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv (32 - 2) \pmod 5</m>,
                    which means that <m>\left(m^5 - m \right) \equiv 0 \pmod 5</m>.
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
